Here is an example of a Java program that reads a file and prints its content to the console:

```java
import java.io.BufferedReader;
import java.io.FileReader;
import java.io.IOException;

public class FileReaderExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String fileName = "example_file.txt"; // Replace with your file name

        try (BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(fileName))) {
            String line;
            while ((line = br.readLine()) != null) {
                System.out.println(line);
            }
        } catch (IOException e) {
            System.err.println("Error reading file: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
```
This Java program uses a `BufferedReader` and `FileReader` to read the content of a file line by line. It starts by defining the name of the file you want to read (replace `"example_file.txt"` with your desired file).

The code then uses a `try-with-resources` block to automatically close the file reader after it is no longer needed, which handles resource management and avoids memory leaks.

If an error occurs while reading the file, such as a file not found or permission denied, the program will catch the `IOException` exception and print an error message to the console.

To use this code, save it in a .java file and compile it with your preferred Java compiler. Then, run the compiled class to execute the program. The output of the program will be printed to the console.

